[136.987146, "o", "Recommended Classification Threshold\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> ------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> We recommend setting the decision threshold to exactly 0.644. \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[136.989962, "o", "> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> Why this threshold?\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Operational Feasibility: Our manual investigation team of 12 analysts has a hard capacity limit of 1,500 alerts/day. At a threshold of 0.644, the model flags approximately 1,480.3 alerts per day. This represents a 98.7% capacity utilization rate, meaning the team can handle the volume without any additional headcount or backlog buildup.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Cost-Benefit Optimization: Under the constraint that daily alerts must not exceed 1,500, a threshold of 0.644 is the mathematically optimal choice. It minimizes the total quarterly cost to $192.73M. Lower thresholds would generate a volume of alerts that our team cannot review, while higher thresholds would let too many high-loss fraud cases go undetected.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> Expected Financial Impact (Per Quarter)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> ---------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> Based on Finance-validated cost parameters ($4,200 loss per undetected fraud case, $35 cost per manual investigation) and our quarterly transaction volume of 2,800,000, we have modeled the financial outcomes for different operational scenarios:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> 1. Baseline Scenario: No Model Deployed (Flag Nothing)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Description: All fraud cases pass through undetected. We incur no manual investigation costs but suffer full fraud losses.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Fraud Loss: $448,110,562.69\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Investigation Cost: $0.00\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Total Quarterly Cost: $448,110,562.69\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> 2. Feasible Deployment Scenario: Tuned Model (Threshold = 0.644)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.990736, "o", "   - Description: The model is deployed with the recommended threshold. Daily alerts are capped within team capacity.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Fraud Loss (Undetected Fraud): $188,067,127.34  (representing 44,778 undetected fraud cases)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Investigation Cost: $4,662,981.24  (representing 133,228 investigations)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Total Quarterly Cost: $192,730,108.59\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Net Quarterly Savings vs. Baseline: $255,380,454.10\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[136.990822, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.990885, "o", "3. Analyst Draft Scenario: Unfeasible Model (Threshold = 0.5)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.991035, "o", "   - Description: This is the default threshold recommended by the analyst. It is operationally impossible because it flags 4,287.4 alerts per day (285.8% of team capacity).\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[136.991205, "o", ">    - Fraud Loss (Undetected Fraud): $113,769,002.96\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>    - Investigation Cost: $13,505,231.98  (assuming all could be investigated)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[136.991256, "o", "\u001b[?2004h>    - Total Quarterly Cost: $127,274,234.95\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.991743, "o", "   - Note: Because our team capacity is capped at 1,500 alerts/day, we would actually not be able to achieve these savings. The unreviewed alerts would overflow, leading to unmitigated fraud and a breakdown of fraud operations.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.991935, "o", "Daily Operational Volume and Capacity Fit\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> -----------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> At the recommended threshold of 0.644:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.992015, "o", "- Daily Transaction Volume: 31,111.11 transactions/day\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.992218, "o", "- Daily Flagged Transactions (Alerts): 1,480.3 alerts/day (an alert rate of 4.76% of transactions)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.992352, "o", "- Capacity Capacity Margin: 19.7 alerts/day remaining before reaching the 1,500 limit.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.992587, "o", "- Capacity Status: FITS. No additional hiring or overtime is required. The team will operate at maximum efficiency, blocking a substantial amount of fraud while keeping the workload manageable.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[136.992623, "o", "> Strategic Next Steps\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[136.99268, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.992727, "o", "--------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[136.993208, "o", "1. Fix Upstream Scoring Pipeline: Prioritize an engineering ticket to investigate why 585 out-of-bounds records (including 500 duplicates) were included in the raw export. Ensure the scoring pipeline does not re-score or append duplicate records in production.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[136.993262, "o", "> "]
[136.993956, "o", "2. Implement Dynamic Thresholding: As fraud operations capacity grows (e.g., if we hire more analysts) or if we implement automation tools that lower the cost of investigation below $35, we can lower the threshold (down towards 0.29) to capture more fraud and unlock additional millions of dollars in savings.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \"\"\"\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> with open('/output/recommendation.txt', 'w') as f:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h>     f.write(text)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> print(\"Saved recommendation.txt successfully!\")\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[136.994053, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> EOF\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
